California Housing Prices Dataset¶

As Labwork 5 assignment, I analysed California Housing Prices Dataset and tried to predict house prices based on given features. For this purpose, I used 2 different method for prediction. Firstly, I binned the house prices due to the polynomial distribution of house prices and used classification methods to predict groups. Secondly, I used 5 different regression algorithms to predict house prices with different pre-process steps.

In [ ]:
def log_transform(s, reverse=False):
    if reverse:
        return np.exp(s)-1
    else:
        return np.log(s+1)
In [ ]:
#Dropping missing values
data2 = data.dropna().reset_index(drop = True)

# Encoding ocean_proximity column
data2['<1H OCEAN'] = data.loc[:,"ocean_proximity"] == "<1H OCEAN"
data2['INLAND'] = data.loc[:,"ocean_proximity"] == "INLAND"
data2['NEAR OCEAN'] = data.loc[:,"ocean_proximity"] == "NEAR OCEAN"
data2['NEAR BAY'] = data.loc[:,"ocean_proximity"] == "NEAR BAY"

# Outlier detection and removing with Isolation Forest
X = data2.drop(["median_house_value","ocean_proximity"],axis=1)
y = data2.median_house_value

clf = IsolationForest(random_state=42, contamination=.1)
clf.fit(X)
y_pred_train = clf.predict(X)

X_rem = X[np.where(y_pred_train == 1, True, False)]
y_rem = y[X_rem.index]

X_rem = X_rem.reset_index(drop=True) 
y_rem = y_rem.reset_index(drop=True)

Bucketing Median House Value and Classification¶

Due to the Polynomial Probability Distribution of the Median House Value column, we can try bucketing this column and convert numeric values into categoric groups based on theri quantiles.

Model Building¶

In [ ]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import  train_test_split, cross_validate
from sklearn.feature_selection import RFE, SelectKBest, chi2, SelectFromModel

# Splitting

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_rem, y_rem_b, test_size=0.15, random_state=42)

# Feature Selection
selector = SelectFromModel(RandomForestClassifier()).fit(X_train, y_train)

X_rnd_train = selector.transform(X_train)
X_rnd_test = selector.transform(X_test)

rnd_features = X_rem.loc[:,selector.get_support()].columns.tolist()
print("Selected Columns:",rnd_features,"\n")

# Model Building
rnd = RandomForestClassifier(random_state = 42)

cv = cross_validate(rnd,X_rnd_train,y_train,cv = 3, n_jobs=-1, return_estimator=True)
print("Mean training accuracy: {}".format(np.mean(cv['test_score'])))
print("Test accuracy: {}".format(cv["estimator"][0].score(X_rnd_test,y_test)))
print("Accuracy Scores of cross valdations: {}".format(cv['test_score']))

from sklearn.metrics import r2_score
import lightgbm as lgb
params = {}
params['learning_rate'] = 0.01
params['boosting_type'] = 'gbdt'
params['objective'] = 'regression'
params['num_leaves'] = 10
params['max_depth'] = 100
params['reg_alpha'] = 0.001
params['min_child_samples'] = 20
params['n_estimators'] = 10000
params['random_state'] = 42

models = lgb.LGBMRegressor(
    objective = params['objective'],
    n_estimators= params['n_estimators'],
    random_state = params['random_state'],
    boosting_type = params['boosting_type'],
    num_leaves = params['num_leaves'],
    reg_alpha = params['reg_alpha'],
    min_child_samples = params['min_child_samples'],
    learning_rate = params['learning_rate'],
    max_depth = params['max_depth'],

)

selector = SelectFromModel(models).fit(X_train, y_train)

X_lgb_train = selector.transform(X_train)
X_lgb_test = selector.transform(X_test)

lgb_features = X_train.loc[:,selector.get_support()].columns.tolist()
print("Selected Columns:",lgb_features,"\n")

s = time()
cv = cross_validate(models,X_lgb_train,y_train,cv = 3, n_jobs=-1, return_estimator=True)
f = time()
print("Mean training accuracy: {}".format(np.mean(cv['test_score'])))
print("Test accuracy: {}".format(cv["estimator"][0].score(X_lgb_test,y_test)))
print("CV Scores: {}".format(cv['test_score']))
print("Test Adjusted R-squared Value:",1 - (1-cv["estimator"][0].score(X_lgb_test,y_test))*(len(y_test)-1)/(len(y_test)-X_lgb_test.shape[1]-1))
print("Passed time:",f-s)

Conclusion¶

Firstly, I tried binning our label due to binomial distribution and try to solve problem with classification methods. After many trails over the bin number, I could not obtain good accuracy. During the regression approach, I applied log transformation to skewed features and label, encode ocean_proximity feature and generate new label based on geographical information. After these preprocessings, I applied 5 different algorithms: Lasso, Ridge, LightGBM, Random Forest Regressor and XGBoost. Due to the time condition, I tried to optimize hyperparameters manually. LighGBM and Random Forest performed the best results. If we check the Adjusted R-sqaured values of these algortihms, we see that LightGBM regressor gave the best result with 0.84933. However, Random Forest is faster than LightGBM.
